'''King Achilla Rufino Orru Apaa-idomo''' was a [[Uganda]]-born blind musician whose primary instrument was the [[mbira|lukembé]]. His ethnic background was [[Karamojong people|Karamojong]].
Orru came to Canada as a refugee in 1989. While studying international development at [[Dalhousie University]] in [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]], he started a band, '''Baana Afrique''', which he reformed with local musicians when he moved to [[Toronto]] after graduation in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|last=Skills for Change|first=Pioneers for Change|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GD-EHA-9a64|title=2009 New Pioneers Award (Arts)|accessdate=April 18, 2009}}</ref>
In Toronto, Orru was also well known as a [[Toronto Transit Commission|TTC]] [[Toronto subway and RT|subway]] musician, often playing at [[Bloor-Yonge (TTC)|Bloor-Yonge]] subway station.<ref>{{cite news|last=Daubs|first=Katie|title=News reporter|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2013/02/13/ttc_musician_achilla_orru_renowned_lokembe_player_dead_at_53.html|accessdate=March 3, 2013|newspaper=Toronto Star|date=Feb 13, 2013}}</ref>
Orru's 2004 album ''Dho-Mach'' (Sacred Gift) was nominated for the 2005 [[Juno Awards of 2005|Juno Award]] for World Music Album of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dho-Mach|first=(Sacred Gift)|title=title track|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XGk-u1zJgEw}}</ref>
Orru died on February 4, 2013 at the age of 53.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bagambiire|first=Davies|url=http://www.ugandandiasporanews.com/2013/02/06/the-toronto-community-mourns-the-passing-of-achilla-rufino-orru|title=The Ugandan Toronto Community Mourns The Passing of Achilla Rufino Orru|accessdate=February 6, 2013}}</ref>
