{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}
'''Brent Barraclough''' is a [[classical music|classical]] [[pianist]] and [[film producer]] who was born in [[Canada]] in 1962 and is of [[British Citizenship]]. He studied piano at the [[Juilliard School]] ([[New York City|New York]]) and [[McGill University]] ([[Montreal]]). His principal piano teachers were [[Ruth Laredo]], "America's First Lady of the Piano"<ref>[http://www.ruthlaredo.com/ Ruth Laredo]</ref> and Thomas C. Plaunt.<ref>[http://people.mcgill.ca/thomas.plaunt/ Thomas Plaunt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404131357/http://people.mcgill.ca/thomas.plaunt/ |date=4 April 2009 }}</ref> He also studied business and philosophy at [[New York University]], [[University of Toronto]], and [[Sauder School of Business]] (University of British Columbia).<ref>[https://archive.is/20140511015422/http://www.rjhf.com/html/2012_Adjudicator_BB.html Hnatyshyn Foundation]</ref>
He is known for his work as actor and producer in both ''The French Guy''<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0476657/ The French Guy]</ref> and ''2 Days Later with Jools Holland''.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0973778/ 2 Days Later with Jools Holland]</ref> He was a national Director of The Drake Music Project<ref>[http://www.drakemusicproject.org/ The Drake Music Project]</ref> and Chief Executive of "Live Music Now!"<ref>[http://www.artsdata.net/wwwr1/keywordsearch.asp?Query=london Live Music Now!]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in [[London, England]]. He was also host of the [[Shaw Cable]] TV show ''Noteworthy'' in the early 1980s.
He was elected as a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] (U.K.) in 2001.<ref>[http://www.thersa.org/ The Royal Society of Arts]</ref> The RSA is a prestigious society that includes among its former members [[Benjamin Franklin]], [[Charles Dickens]] and [[John Diefenbaker]].
He is a member of [https://www.americanbachsociety.org The American Bach Society].
In 2012 he served on the Hnatyshyn Foundation Piano Jury with Anton Kuerti and Louise Bissette.<ref>[https://archive.is/20140511015339/http://www.rjhf.com/html/daadjudicators12-e.html Hnatyshyn Foundation]</ref>
His official website is: http://www.brentbarraclough.com/
