====Video games====

* In the video game ''[[The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion]]'' (2006), the player can temporarily acquire "Boots of Springheel Jak", which allow the player to jump substantially higher and safely fall from greater heights.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}
* In the video game ''[[Assassin's Creed Syndicate]]'' (2015), [[Charles Dickens]] assigns the player to investigate the true nature of Spring-heeled Jack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/wikis/assassins-creed-syndicate/Spring-Heeled_Jack|title=Spring-Heeled Jack - Assassin's Creed Syndicate Wiki Guide - IGN|website=IGN|language=en|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>

==In other countries==
A similar figure known as [[Pérák, the Spring Man of Prague]] was reported to have been seen in [[Czechoslovakia]] around 1939–1945. As writers such as [[Mike Dash]] have shown, the elusiveness and supernatural leaping abilities attributed to Pérák bear a close resemblance to those exhibited by Spring-heeled Jack, and distinct parallels can be drawn between the two entities.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> The stories of Pérák provide a useful example of how the traits of Spring-heeled Jack have a broad cultural resonance in urban folklore. Pérák, like Spring-heeled Jack, went on to become a folklore hero, even starring in several animated superhero cartoons, fighting the [[Schutzstaffel|SS]], the earliest of which is [[Jiří Trnka]]'s 1946 film ''Pérák a SS'' or ''[[Springman and the SS]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sites/bfi.org.uk/files/downloads/bfi-press-release-jiri-trnka-at-bfi-southbank-in-april-2012-03-06.pdf|title="Jiří Trnka At BFI Southbank in April 2012", (Trnka Shorts for Adults) BFI press release March 2012.|publisher=}}</ref>

